docs.abstract: As the music industry reckons with racial inequality, one of the first old structures to fall has been a term that dates back to the 1970s.
docs.snippet: As the music industry reckons with racial inequality, one of the first old structures to fall has been a term that dates back to the 1970s.
docs.lead_paragraph: The ongoing protests against police brutality in the United States are beginning to bring wider change and reflection. Over the last two weeks, that’s meant that the music business, long a site of racial inequity, has been the subject of a reckoning. One of the first old structures to fall has been the category “urban” music, a quirk of nomenclature that goes back more than four decades, and has become such an elastic term that it’s almost lost all meaning.

headline.main: The Long, Complicated History of ‘Urban’ Music

docs.abstract: Black- and Latino-owned businesses have suffered damage from vandals and arsonists on the fringes of the protests over police brutality. Non-bank community lenders are out to protect them.
docs.snippet: Black- and Latino-owned businesses have suffered damage from vandals and arsonists on the fringes of the protests over police brutality. Non-bank community lenders are out to protect them.
docs.lead_paragraph: On Tuesday evening in Ferguson, Mo., a dozen people formed a human chain around Reds The One and Only BBQ, a restaurant. Vandals had smashed other storefronts in the area amid protests over the killing of George Floyd in police custody, but Reds was still standing.

headline.main: For Some Minority-Owned Businesses, Their Lenders Are Now Their Defenders
headline.print_headline: Lenders Hit The Streets To Protect Small Firms

docs.abstract: Five were slated to make their Broadway debuts. Now? They’re bunking with family, grappling with unemployment and fighting injustice.

docs.lead_paragraph: Back in February, Hiram Delgado quit his wait staff job at Dock Asian Eatery in Bushwick, Brooklyn. “Hey,” he told his boss, “I’m not going to be able to work here anymore because I’m going to be on Broadway.”

headline.main: For the Actors of ‘Take Me Out,’ a Coming-Out Party Is Postponed

docs.abstract: The acronym, which stands for black, Indigenous and people of color, is suddenly everywhere. Is it doing its job?
docs.snippet: The acronym, which stands for black, Indigenous and people of color, is suddenly everywhere. Is it doing its job?
docs.lead_paragraph: Black Americans have been called by many names in the United States. African-American, Negro, colored and the unutterable slur that rhymes with bigger. In recent weeks, as protests against police brutality and racism have flooded the streets and social media, another more inclusive term has been ascribed to the population: BIPOC.

docs.abstract: The books we read, the movies we watch, the friends we make, the doctors we visit and the conversations we have at home all shape our children’s views of race.
docs.snippet: The books we read, the movies we watch, the friends we make, the doctors we visit and the conversations we have at home all shape our children’s views of race.
docs.lead_paragraph: When kids on the gaming site Roblox were darkening the skin color of their avatars to support Black Lives Matter, 12-year-old Garvey Mortley decided to speak up. She created a video explaining the offensive history of blackface, and offered viewers more appropriate ways they could show support.

headline.main: How to Raise an Anti-Racist Kid

docs.abstract: Demonstrators had tried to topple the statue of Frank Rizzo, the former mayor and police commissioner accused of police abuses in the 1960s and ’70s.
docs.snippet: Demonstrators had tried to topple the statue of Frank Rizzo, the former mayor and police commissioner accused of police abuses in the 1960s and ’70s.
docs.lead_paragraph: PHILADELPHIA — The city of Philadelphia took a step to heal a notable scar from its past early Wednesday morning by quietly removing the statue of the former mayor Frank Rizzo, who took a confrontational approach to black and gay people as police commissioner in the 1960s and ’70s.

headline.main: Philadelphia Removes Statue Seen as Symbol of Racism and Police Abuse
